studies in Canada, followed by close readings of five novels that rewrite the Mennonite break event through specific strains of emphasis, including a religious narrative, ethnic narrative, trauma narrative, and meta-narrative. The result is thoughtful and engaging exploration of the shifting contours of Mennonite collective identity, and an exciting new methodology that promises to resituate the discourse of migrant writing in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian fiction (English)xMennonite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexMennonite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEmigration and immigration in literature. 0aMennonitesxCanada. 0aMennonitesxIn literature. 0aMennonitesxSoviet Union. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aMennonite.  aRussian Mennonite.  adiaspora.  aethnicity.  aimmigration.  aliterature.  anarrative.  atrauma.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755448340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554483423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554483/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles